figgy.title: Bad Tiffs in PPPL Technical Report

comments.body: Someone reingested

Replacements proposed:
- [Uppy](https://uppy.io/), [Shrine](https://shrinerb.com/)
   - pros
      - we could also move away from dropzone and have a more consistent experience
   - cons
      - These are both fully-featured upload tools; they're going to provide a lot more than we need.
      - neither has a plugin for selecting a file that's already on the server.
      - even if we write our own plugin it will probably be much more complex logic than if we write something specifically to our own use case
- [Vue finder](https://vue-finder.netlify.app/), tool mentioned during structure manager design discussion
   - pros
      - simple tool, feature set matches our needs pretty well -- show files, navigate them, some event handling
      - small, well-organized code base
      - good documentation
      - some keyboard navigation possible
   - cons
      - single developer, however they are currently actively engaged
      - doesn't yet support vue 3, although there is a pre-release
- [jstree](https://www.jstree.com/)
   - pros
      - This is the tool we use for pulfalight, so some consistency in dependency choice
      - Similar to the current UI, some consistency for users
      - has a fuzzy search feature
   - cons
      - a jquery plugin is probably not as good a fit as a vue component
      - solo developer
      - more features than we likely need

comments.body:
@mccalluc I don't disagree that smaller headers (h3 or h4) might be useful. However, h1 and h2 create a visual distraction in our log that will make it harder to quickly find the change content, as the present design of this feature favors showing the message content. I would have liked to have messages and changes separated. I keep pointing to the example of provenance used for PSU ScholarSphere to understand what I want to capture. That example shows a clean, standardized timeline of changes to the record. The messaging feature, which is also important, somehow got blended. Perhaps it's something we can talk about separating in the future. 

## Image shows provenance example
![Screen Shot 2022-12-02 at 9 45 36 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/50670293/205319210-aec81a35-1083-4f33-999f-133a1c53a406.jpeg)

## Specific things that are desirable
- The beaded line allows me to quickly differentiate between changes. This doesn't mean we need to do exactly the same thing, but the result is desired.
- The entries are standardized and look clean. I think part of the difference is each change is its own entry, rather than lumping them together.
- Another difference is showing the change and date before who made the change. Preference towards the person is important for the message feature. We do need to know who made a change, but it isn't the first thing we need to know, unlike in the message feature.

Bess points out that this is better solved with CSS. Closing this PR, will clarify approach in the orig issue. For the rest, I've copied all these comments into the [agenda for the 12/7 meeting](https://docs.google.com/document/d/14SjoKlTI7AWNVNjgBOa28jDnhClTnaMnEgN5EBocR9o/edit#): We can talk them over and file granular issues.
